We had to do some last-minute shopping on our way home from somewhere on Xmas Eve, so we stopped at Target and decided to bring the boys in because we didn’t want to leave them in the freezing car! Brady was looking forward to meeting as many new frens as possible, but no one even seemed to notice them, except for the cashier who just gave them a weird look 🤣. I guess people were too preoccupied with last minute shopping. 

Update: thanks for all your comments regarding pets not being allowed in Target! I realize we broke this rule, but it wasn’t just to take this video as some people are implying and I certainly do not think we are entitled in any way! The store was about to close and we BOTH really needed to go in to get last minute things for Christmas day. We decided to bring the boys in since it was below freezing out, and didn’t want to leave them in the car. We were in and out within 15 minutes. Very sorry if us breaking Target’s Pet rules upsets anyone but I think we can all agree that there are worse things going on in the world to be mad about 😬.

Another update - I’m very sorry that bringing Brady and Graffiti inside of Target could negatively impact the disabled community. This did not even cross our mind until reading some of the latest comments (see pinned comment). Thank you to those who have kindly  educated us on this. While I will not take this video down as some are requesting, I will create another reel or post describing why people should adhere to store pet policies for the safety of the disabled community.

Happy Gotcha Day, @graffitithecorgi! 🤗. This was on January 13th, 2018. Poppa and I had just started dating 6 months earlier. I took Brady to the vet on Friday to check progress on his eye injury (he has a corneal abrasion to his left eye, likely from playing at the park). Fortunately it decreased in size after 10 days of using special eye drops, which meant we may not need to see an eye specialist after all, as long as it continues to improve. I was so happy to hear this. However…

He woke up this morning (3 days after seeing the vet in this video) and his eye was swollen shut again unfortunately 😔. I’m not sure what happened. He may have scratched at it while he was sleeping, or, maybe not. I’ve been reading a lot about these injuries and it’s fairly common for eye injuries to improve, then decline for no apparent reason. I’ll be taking him in to the vet again this afternoon.

Given recent events it’s now likely we’ll need to see an eye specialist at the end of the month, who will perform minimally invasive treatment (likely keratotomy or burr debridement) but I will keep you guys posted once we see the vet today.

Brady says the cone of shame ain’t so bad after all. He’s pretty unbothered by it so far 😊. 

We got some pain meds and did another fluorescein stain at the vet today. The abrasion/ulcer has indeed gotten worse. I am certain this is because he scratched his eye in the middle of the night. 

If you are dealing with a corneal ulcer or abrasion, my advice would be to get a cone and wear it immediately and at all times even if the injury is minor and even if your vet doesn’t think it’s needed ❤️. Since he hadn’t been scratching or rubbing at it we decided he would be ok without the cone and I’m deeply regretting this decision…He was almost all healed and now we are back at square one 😞. 

Next steps are to continue with the drops, go for another follow up in a few days then see the eye specialist next Thursday who will likely want to perform either the burr debridement or keratotomy procedure which will help heal the cornea properly. 

Brady is his same happy, spunky self as always and it might take a little longer but he will heal. Momma, poppa and Gdog are taking good care of him so don’t worry too much about him if you are 🥰.

Quick update on Brady’s eye! We visited the vet again yesterday. His corneal ulcer has improved but still isn’t fully healed so we are finally going to see the eye specialist today. We’ll see what the specialist says after the exam, but our vet told us she thinks it’s likely they will do a burr debridement the same day if it’s needed. 

The Burr Debridement Surgery is when they numb the eye and pass a diamond burr over the ulcerated area to remove the damaged tissue, which will help the cornea heal properly. 

Brady has high anxiety during things like this (and with foreign objects as you all know 😅) so I was hoping he wouldn’t need to go through it, but the vet gave us medication for anxiety (trazadone and gabapentin), and it’s supposed to be a pretty quick and easy procedure. 

I’m so proud of Brady for being strong and so patient during all our vet visits and eye drop applications (4 different drops 3 times a day!). 

I will keep you all posted on how it goes! Hopefully we can get rid of this ulcer for good. Please wish Brady luck! ❤️

It’s always a little nerve wracking when putting your dog (especially a senior dog) under anesthesia as there are always risks…and the last time Brady went under was 8 years ago! But his pre-op bloodwork and x-rays were perfect, so we weren’t too worried. 

That said it’s still a HUGE relief to have this done and over with, and to know he’s now super healthy in every way and set up for success for the later years of his life 🙏. 

Thank you Dr. Levy with @vca for taking such great care of Brady and Graffiti and their oral health 🥰.
